The '''Ivory Coast national football team''' ([[French language|French]]: ''Équipe de football de Côte d'Ivoire'', recognized as the '''Côte d'Ivoire''' by [[FIFA]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=FIFA|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/CIV|access-date=|website=fifa.com|language=en|archive-date=6 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211006102124/https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/CIV|url-status=live}}</ref>) represents [[Ivory Coast]] in men's international [[Association football|football]]. Nicknamed ''the Elephants'', the team is managed by the [[Ivorian Football Federation]] (FIF). The team has won the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] three times, in [[1992 African Cup of Nations|1992]], [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]] and [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]], and has qualified for the [[FIFA World Cup]] four times, in [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006]], [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]], [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]] and [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026.]]

Ivory Coast's home colours are all orange. Since 2020 their home games have been played at [[Alassane Ouattara Stadium]], in Abidjan. Prior to this their home ground was [[Felix Houphouet Boigny Stadium]], also in Abidjan. [[Didier Zokora]] holds the record for number of caps, with 123. The nation's leading goalscorer is [[Didier Drogba]], who scored 65 goals for ''the Elephants'' in 105 appearances.

==History==
===Early history: 1960s–1980s===
The team played its first international match against [[Benin national football team|Dahomey]], now known as [[Benin]], which they won 3{{ndash}}2 on 13 April 1960 in [[Madagascar]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jeux Sportifs de la Communauté Française 1960 (Tananarive) |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesc/communaute-fr60.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref>

The team achieved an 11{{ndash}}0 victory against the [[Central African Republic|Central African Republic national football team]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ivory Coast - List of International Matches |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesi/ivo-intres.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref> In 1961 the team made their first appearance in the [[Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ivory Coast national football team - history and facts |url=https://www.footballhistory.org/national/ivory-coast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.footballhistory.org}}</ref> After gaining independence from [[France]], the team finished third in the [[1963 Africa Cup of Nations|1963]] and [[1965 Africa Cup of Nations|1965]] tournaments.{{Citation needed|date=November 2025}}

Ivory Coast's performances in the 1970s were mixed. In the [[1970 African Cup of Nations]], the team finished top of their group, but lost to Ghana – the powerhouses of African football at the time – in the semi-finals, and went on to finish 4th after losing the third-place play-off to the [[Egypt national football team|United Arab Republic]] (now Egypt).<ref>{{Cite web |title=African Nations Cup 1970 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/70a.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref> They failed to qualify for [[1972 Africa Cup of Nations|the 1972 edition]], losing 4–3 to [[Congo national football team|Congo-Brazzaville]] in the final qualifying round,<ref>{{Cite web |title=African Nations Cup 1972 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/72a.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref> and then qualified in [[1974 Africa Cup of Nations|1974]] but finished bottom of their group with only a single point.<ref>{{Cite web |title=African Nations Cup 1974 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/74a.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref> Missing the [[1976 Africa Cup of Nations|1976]] tournament,<ref>{{Cite web |title=African Nations Cup 1976 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/76a.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref> the team initially qualified for [[1978 Africa Cup of Nations|1978]], beating [[Mali national football team|Mali]] 2–1 on aggregate, but were disqualified for fielding an ineligible player in the second leg. Mali were also disqualified, due to police and stadium security assaulting the match officials during the first leg, resulting in [[Burkina Faso national football team|Upper Volta]], who Ivory Coast had beaten in the first qualifying round, inheriting their place.<ref>{{Cite web |title=African Nations Cup 1978 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/78a.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref>

In [[1984 Africa Cup of Nations|1984]], the team hosted the African Cup of Nations for the first time, but failed to get out of their group.<ref>{{Cite web |title=African Nations Cup 1984 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/84a.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref> In [[1986 Africa Cup of Nations|1986]], they narrowly qualified from their group on goals scored, and went on to finish third once more, beating Morocco 3–2 in the third-place play-off.<ref>{{Cite web |title=African Nations Cup 1986 |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tables/86a.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=www.rsssf.org}}</ref>

===1990s===
At the [[1992 Africa Cup of Nations]], Ivory Coast beat [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] 3{{ndash}}0<ref>{{Cite web |date=1992-01-13 |title=AFCON 1992 : Ivory Coast beats Algeria 3-0 |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/1992/finals/group-c/1992-01-13-ivorycoast-algeria.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> and drew 0{{ndash}}0 with Congo to finish top of their group.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1992-01-13 |title=Ivory Coast draws with Congo-Brazzaville to reach AFCON quarterfinals |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/1992/finals/group-c/1992-01-15-ivorycoast-congobrazzaville.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> An extra-time victory over Zambia<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ivory Coast beats Zambia in extra time to advance to AFCON semifinals |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/1992/finals/second-round/1992-01-20-ivorycoast-zambia.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> and a penalty shoot-out win over Cameroon<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ivory Coast beats Cameroon in shoot out to reach AFCON final |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/1992/finals/second-round/1992-01-23-cameroon-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> took them to the final for the first time, where they faced Ghana. The match again went to a penalty shoot-out, which became, at the time, the highest-scoring in international football; Ivory Coast eventually triumphed 11–10 to win the title for the first time.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ivory Coast beats Ghana in shoot out to win 1992 AFCON |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/1992/finals/second-round/1992-01-26-ivorycoast-ghana.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> They were unable to defend their title in [[1994 Africa Cup of Nations|1994]], losing to [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nigeria beats Ivory Coast in shoot out to reach AFCON final |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/1994/finals/second-round/1994-04-06-nigeria-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

===2000s and World Cup debut===
In October 2005, Ivory Coast secured qualification for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], their first-ever appearance at the tournament. Having been drawn into a "[[group of death]]" that also featured Cameroon and Egypt, Ivory Coast went into the final match second behind Cameroon, but qualified after beating Sudan 3–1 while Cameroon could only draw with Egypt.<ref>{{Cite web |title=World Cup 2006 Qualifiers : Ivory Coast beats Sudan 3-1 to qualify for 2006 World Cup |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2006/qualifiers/caf/second-round-group-3/2005-10-08-sudan-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

Ivory Coast finished runners-up at the [[2006 African Cup of Nations]], with the tournament including another lengthy penalty shootout, where Ivory Coast defeated [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] 12–11.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ivory Coast beats Cameroon in shoot out to advance to AFCON semifinals |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/2006/finals/second-round/2006-02-04-cameroon-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

In the tournament itself, Ivory Coast were drawn into another group of death, against [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]], [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], and [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|Serbia and Montenegro]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=2006 FIFA World Cup |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2006 |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> They lost 2–1 to Argentina<ref>{{Cite web |date=2006-06-10 |title=World Cup 2006 : Argentina defeats Ivory Coast 2-1 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2006/finals/group-c/2006-06-10-argentina-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> – with [[Didier Drogba]] scoring the team's first-ever World Cup goal in the 82nd minute – and then 2–1 to the Netherlands,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2006-06-10 |title=World Cup 2006 : Netherlands defeats Ivory Coast 2-1 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2006/finals/group-c/2006-06-16-netherlands-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> meaning they had already been eliminated by the time they played Serbia and Montenegro. After going 2–0 down after just 20 minutes, Ivory Coast came back to win 3–2, with [[Bonaventure Kalou]] scoring an 86th-minute penalty to give Ivory Coast their first-ever World Cup victory.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2006-06-10 |title=World Cup 2006 : Serbia and Montenegro and Ivory Coast eliminated from FIFA World Cup |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2006/finals/group-c/2006-06-21-ivorycoast-serbiaandmontenegro.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

After [[Uli Stielike]] left before the [[2008 African Cup of Nations]] due to his son's health, co-trainer Gerard Gili took his position.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Reuters |date=2008-01-20 |title=Ivory Coast coach Stielike will not rejoin squad |url=https://timesofmalta.com/article/ivory-coast-coach-stielike-will-not-rejoin-squad.192661 |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=Times of Malta |language=en-gb}}</ref> To compensate of the lack of another co-coach, Didier Drogba acted as a player-coach. This was only the second time that a player had also acted as a coach at the tournament, after [[George Weah]] was both player and coach for [[Liberia national football team|Liberia]] during the [[2002 African Cup of Nations|2002 tournament]].

===2010s===
[[File:Cote d'Iviore NT 2010.jpg|thumb|The national football team of the Côte d'Ivoire before a match against Poland in 2010]]

Ivory Coast qualified for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] in [[South Africa]], and were again drawn in a group of death, against five-time champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], and [[North Korea national football team|North Korea]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2010-06-15 |title=World Cup 2010 : Group G |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2010/finals/group-g |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> Having managed a 0–0 draw against Portugal,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2010-06-15 |title=World Cup 2010 : Ivory Coast and Portugal play out 0-0 draw |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2010/finals/group-g/2010-06-15-ivorycoast-portugal.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> a 3–1 defeat to Brazil meant that in order to qualify from their group,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2010-06-15 |title=World Cup 2010 : Brazil defeats Ivory Coast 3-1 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2010/finals/group-g/2010-06-20-brazil-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> they would have to beat North Korea,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=2010-06-15 |title=World Cup 2010 : North Korea and Ivory Coast both exit FIFA World Cup |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2010/finals/group-g/2010-06-25-northkorea-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> while Brazil needed to beat Portugal, and thanks to Portugal's 7–0 win over North Korea,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2010-06-15 |title=World Cup 2010 : Portugal beats North Korea 7-0 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2010/finals/group-g/2010-06-21-portugal-northkorea.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> there needed to be a substantial swing in goal difference. Ivory Coast won 3–0,<ref name=":0" /> but Portugal held Brazil to a 0–0 draw<ref>{{Cite web |date=2010-06-15 |title=World Cup 2010 : Portugal and Brazil qualify for the Round of 16 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2010/finals/group-g/2010-06-25-portugal-brazil.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> and Ivory Coast were once again eliminated in the group stage.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2010-06-15 |title=World Cup 2010 : Group G |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2010/finals/group-g |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

[[File:FIF NewCrest.png|thumb|left|100px|Logo until 2014]]

The team made a third appearance in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] in [[Brazil]], where they were drawn into [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group C|Group C]] against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]], [[Greece national football team|Greece]], and [[Japan national football team|Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2014-06-14 |title=World Cup 2014 : Group C |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2014/finals/group-c |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> After coming from behind to beat Japan 2–1,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2014-06-14 |title=World Cup 2014 : Ivory Coast beats Japan 2-1 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2014/finals/group-c/2014-06-14-ivorycoast-japan.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> Ivory Coast then lost 2–1 to Colombia,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2014-06-14 |title=World Cup 2014 : Colombia defeats Ivory Coast 2-1 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2014/finals/group-c/2014-06-19-colombia-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> leaving their qualification in the balance. In their final match against Greece, the score was 1–1 going into stoppage time, and with Japan losing 4–1 to Colombia, Ivory Coast looked set to qualify. However, in the 93rd minute, [[Giovanni Sio]] gave away a penalty which [[Georgios Samaras]] converted, giving Greece both the victory and the place in the last 16;<ref>{{Cite web |date=2014-06-14 |title=World Cup 2014 : Greece beats Ivory Coast 2-1 to qualify for the Round of 16 |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2014/finals/group-c/2014-06-24-greece-ivorycoast.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref> Ivory Coast, meanwhile, went out in the group stage for the third tournament in a row.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2014-06-14 |title=World Cup 2014 : Group C |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2014/finals/group-c |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

In 2015, the national team won the [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|Africa Cup of Nations]] for the second time in [[Equatorial Guinea]], defeating [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] in a 22-shot penalty shootout, winning 9–8 after a scoreless game.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ivory Coast beats Ghana in shoot out to win 2015 AFCON |url=https://athlet.org/football/can/2015/finals/second-round/2015-02-08-ivorycoast-ghana.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

Ivory Coast failed to qualify for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]]. After needing a win in their final match against [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]], they lost 2–0, meaning Morocco qualified instead.<ref>{{Cite web |title=World Cup 2018 Qualifiers : Morocco beats Ivory Coast 2-0 to qualify for 2018 World Cup |url=https://athlet.org/football/world-cup/2018/qualifiers/caf/third-round-c/2017-11-11-ivorycoast-morocco.html |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=athlet.org}}</ref>

=== 2020s ===
[[File:Equipe de la Cote d'Ivoire.jpg|thumb|200px|The national football team of the Côte d'Ivoire in 2022]]
In early 2024, Ivory Coast hosted the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|Africa Cup of Nations]] for the second time.<ref>{{cite web |date=30 January 2019 |title=Cote d'Ivoire agrees CAF timetable shift |url=https://www.cafonline.com/news-center/news/cote-d-ivoire-agrees-caf-timetable-shift |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111091908/https://www.cafonline.com/news-center/news/cote-d-ivoire-agrees-caf-timetable-shift |archive-date=11 January 2022 |access-date=1 September 2019 |website=[[Confederation of African Football|CAFOnline.com]]}}</ref> Following a 4–0 defeat to [[Equatorial Guinea national football team|Equatorial Guinea]] and third-placed finish in the group stage, coach [[Jean-Louis Gasset]] was dismissed, and assistant coach [[Emerse Faé]] was hired as caretaker in the knockout stages, as the national team qualified as one of the best third-placed teams.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jean-Louis Gasset no longer Cote d'Ivoire head coach |url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/jean-louis-gasset-no-longer-cote-d-ivoire-head-coach/ |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=Jean-Louis Gasset no longer Cote d’Ivoire head coach |language=en-GB}}</ref> Later on, Ivory Coast managed to defeat the defending champions [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] in the penalty shoot-outs, [[Mali national football team|Mali]] after extra-time, and [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2024/02/11/sport/afcon-final-nigeria-ivory-coast-spt-intl/index.html |title=Host nation Ivory Coast continues miraculous run to AFCON final to set up a matchup against Nigeria |publisher=CNN |date=11 February 2024 |access-date=14 February 2024 |archive-date=14 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240214133701/https://edition.cnn.com/2024/02/11/sport/afcon-final-nigeria-ivory-coast-spt-intl/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> They eventually won the title, defeating Nigeria 2–1 in the final, marking their third victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68196261 |title=Nigeria 1–2 Ivory Coast |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 February 2024 |access-date=14 February 2024 |archive-date=12 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240212182429/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68196261 |url-status=live }}</ref> For the first time in the history of the African Cup of Nations, the tournament was won by a team that changed coaches during the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |last=video |first=From nearly eliminated in the group stage to champions That was the incredible journey of the "Elephants" to ultimate glory Here's how they did it A. must-watch |title=Ivory Coast's Miraculous AFCON 2023 Triumph: From Rock Bottom to African Glory |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/africa-cup-of-nations/articles-video/ivory-coast-s-miraculous-afcon-2023-triumph-from-rock-bottom-to-african-glory-2024-12-24 |access-date=2025-11-08 |website=beIN SPORTS |language=en-us}}</ref>

==Home stadium==
From 1964 to 2020, [[Felix Houphouet Boigny Stadium]], a 50,000-seater stadium in [[Abidjan]] was the main venue used to host home matches. In 2020, the 60,000-seat [[Alassane Ouattara Stadium]], also in Abidjan, was opened ahead of the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{Cite news|date=2020-10-05|title=AFCON 2023: Ivory Coast opens 60,000-seater stadium|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/10/afcon-2023-ivory-coast-opens-60000-seater-stadium/|location=Lagos, Nigeria|access-date=2021-09-07|newspaper=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard]]|language=en-US|archive-date=7 September 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210907033301/https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/10/afcon-2023-ivory-coast-opens-60000-seater-stadium/|url-status=live}}</ref>

==Supporters==
Supporters of the Elephants are known to be among the most colorful in Africa. At Ivory Coast matches, the Elephants supporter sections typically include a percussion band that mimics the sounds of an [[elephant]] traveling through a forest.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Merrill |first=Austin |date=2010-06-16 |title=Ivory Coast Draws Against Portugal, but Drums the Place to Life |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2010/06/ivory-coast-draws-against-portugal-but-drums-the-place-to-life |access-date=2025-11-08 |magazine=Vanity Fair |language=en-US}}</ref>

